commit.message:
Avoid accidental truncation of user specified sizes.

`ped_unit_format` calls return rounded MB values, by default. That
could cause the `if` condition to consider values that are close to
each other to be the same. Worse though, the `ped_unit_parse` call
in the following `else if` condition would use the rounded MB
value, and that could really mess things up since the rounded value
could easily end up not being sector aligned (MB != MiB).

Signed-off-by: Jonathan Watt <jwatt@jwatt.org>

Bump to 1.1.0

Grand update:
 - drop support for libparted older than 2.4 (#16)
 - introduce `-n, --partition` to set a partition number when
   dealing with file dumps, /dev/loop and /dev/ram devices (#15)
 - ask confirmation for operations (e.g. FAT32 -> FAT16 conversion),
   add `-f, --force` option to not prompt (#13)
 - do not limit FAT32 usage on small partitions (#11)
 - update changelog (#10)

commit.message:
Allow setting maximum size by keyword "max"

Setting the maximum size requires two steps at the moment:
1. get the maximum size with the info option
2. set the maximum size from the info option

It would be much nicer to combine this. So introduce the keyword
"max" for the size. Use LLONG_MAX internally and reuse code parts
from the info option to set the actual maximum size. Update help
text and man page as well.

Looks like this:
$ fatresize -s max /dev/sdb1

Fixes #5

Signed-off-by: Sebastian Parschauer <sparschauer@suse.de>

Fix a segfault and assert handling

When having a FAT partition already resized to the maximum size and
trying to resize it again to maximum size, then fatresize segfaults
because of end_part being NULL. So check it for NULL and return from
snap_to_boundaries() in this case.

While debugging this, it has been noticed that FAT_ASSERT is
ineffective and the action is not executed with parted >= 2.4. So
add execution of the requested action and define DEBUG to make
PED_ASSERT effective. Also add an assertion for the start_part in
snap_to_boundaries().

Verified by testing and disassembly.
Fixes #6

Signed-off-by: Sebastian Parschauer <sparschauer@suse.de>

Fix getting the device name from partition name

There are many partition device names like e.g. /dev/mmcblk0p1 where
it is not enough to trim the trailing digits to get the disk device
name. Using open() here would depend on a POSIX platform. So do it
like _ped_device_probe() and silence libparted exceptions and try
to get the device with ped_device_get(). Trim further trailing
characters until libparted finds it. Return NULL in get_devname()
if the partition name is invalid. Also adapt the usage warning to
show that an existing device name has to be provided.

References: boo#959181
Fixes #2

Signed-off-by: Sebastian Parschauer <sparschauer@suse.de>
